9
00:00:38,800 --> 00:00:41,640
A complex number has a real part and an

10
00:00:41,640 --> 00:00:44,480
imaginary part, and you can plot it on a two-dimensional

11
00:00:44,480 --> 00:00:45,580
surface.

12
00:00:45,580 --> 00:00:48,310
The two-dimensional surface horizontal axis represents

13
00:00:48,310 --> 00:00:51,040
the real part of the function,

14
00:00:51,040 --> 00:00:54,420
not the function, just the real part of the number.

15
00:00:54,420 --> 00:00:54,719
And the imaginary part is

16
00:00:54,719 --> 00:00:55,019
the real part of the number.

17
00:00:55,020 --> 00:00:57,190
The imaginary part of the number is plotted

18
00:00:57,190 --> 00:00:59,360
on the vertical axis, and a point on this

19
00:00:59,360 --> 00:01:03,040
plane is an imaginary number.

20
00:01:03,040 --> 00:01:09,590
If this is x and the height is y, then

21
00:01:09,590 --> 00:01:16,140
the complex number is z, which is x plus iy.

22
00:01:16,140 --> 00:01:17,960
We could also represent it another way.

23
00:01:17,960 --> 00:01:20,680
We could represent it in terms of a distance,

24
00:01:20,680 --> 00:01:23,400
which we can call r, and an angle that we

25
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:24,400
can call theta.

26
00:01:24,400 --> 00:01:29,960
And now, just from elementary trigonometry, the distance

27
00:01:29,960 --> 00:01:35,520
x is r times the cosine of theta.

28
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:40,460
So that's x is r cosine theta.

29
00:01:40,460 --> 00:01:45,120
And y is r times sine theta.

30
00:01:45,120 --> 00:01:48,400
So i times r sine theta.

31
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:51,320
Or in other words, we could take the r out

32
00:01:51,320 --> 00:01:54,240
of it, factor the r out, and write that z

33
00:01:54,240 --> 00:01:54,280
is the cosine of theta.

34
00:01:54,280 --> 00:01:54,380
So that's x times r cosine theta.

35
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:56,900
So z is equal to r

36
00:01:56,900 --> 00:01:59,400
