are just the coefficients here.

271
00:13:17,280 --> 00:13:19,280
Now those probabilities, of course,

272
00:13:19,280 --> 00:13:21,280
do not completely determine

273
00:13:21,280 --> 00:13:23,280
the complex numbers here.

274
00:13:23,280 --> 00:13:25,280
Why not?

275
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:29,280
Well, if I multiply any complex number

276
00:13:29,280 --> 00:13:31,280
by a pure phase,

277
00:13:31,280 --> 00:13:35,280
it doesn't change its magnitude.

278
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:38,280
If I take a complex number

279
00:13:38,280 --> 00:13:41,280
and I multiply it by e to the i theta,

280
00:13:41,280 --> 00:13:45,280
where theta is any angle,

281
00:13:45,280 --> 00:13:47,280
I get a new number

282
00:13:47,280 --> 00:13:49,280
whose magnitude,

283
00:13:49,280 --> 00:13:51,280
whose alpha star alpha,

284
00:13:51,280 --> 00:13:55,280
is exactly the same as the original starting number.

285
00:13:55,280 --> 00:13:57,280
And so knowing the probabilities

286
00:13:57,280 --> 00:14:00,280
is not enough to completely determine

287
00:14:00,280 --> 00:14:02,280
what these coefficients are.

288
00:14:02,280 --> 00:14:05,280
So there's more information in these coefficients

289
00:14:05,280 --> 00:14:07,280
than just the probabilities.

290
00:14:07,280 --> 00:14:08,280
And we're going to find out

291
00:14:08,280 --> 00:14:11,280
what that additional information is.

292
00:14:11,280 --> 00:14:13,280
But for the moment,

293
00:14:13,280 --> 00:14:16,280
this is...

294
00:14:16,280 --> 00:14:18,280
And of course,

295
00:14:18,280 --> 00:14:20,280
if there's more than two possibilities,

296
00:14:20,280 --> 00:14:22,280
up, down, and sideways,

297
00:14:22,280 --> 00:14:26,280
or up, down, and chocolate chip,

298
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:28,280
then we add another one,

299
00:14:28,280 --> 00:14:30,280
gamma, chocolate chip,

300
00:14:30,280 --> 00:14:32,280
and whatever.

301
00:14:32,280 --> 00:14:34,280
So those are orthonormal...

302
00:14:34,280 --> 00:14:36,280
Those are orthonormal vectors.

303
00:14:36,280 --> 00:14:38,280
And we're going to...

304
00:14:38,280 --> 00:14:40,280
Right.

305
00:14:40,280 --> 00:14:43,280
And we represented them in a particular basis.

306
00:14:43,280 --> 00:14:45,280
The basis of up and down,

307
00:14:45,280 --> 00:14:47,280
we represented them, let's just...

308
00:14:47,280 --> 00:14:52,280
We represented them as...

309
00:14:52,280 --> 00:14:57,280
Up was just one zero.

310
00:14:57,280 --> 00:15:00,280
And down is equal to zero.

311
00:15:00,280 --> 00:15:02,280
And down is equal to one.

312
00:15:02,280 --> 00:15:04,280
They're orthogonal to each other.

313
00:15:04,280 --> 00:15:07,280
They're normalized, both of them.

314
00:15:07,280 --> 00:15:08,780
The sums of the squares

315
00:15:08,780 --> 00:15:10,280
in each individual one is one.

316
00:15:10,280 --> 00:15:13,280
So they're called orthonormal vectors.

317
00:15:13,280 --> 00:15:16,280
Orthogonal and normal.

318
00:15:16,280 --> 00:15:19,280
If we have a higher dimensional vector space

319
00:15:19,280 --> 00:15:21,280
with more possibilities,

320
00:15:21,280 --> 00:15:23,280
chocolate chip,

321
00:15:23,280 --> 00:15:26,280
then we might have three vectors altogether.

322
00:15:26,280 --> 00:15:28,280
Zero, zero, zero.

323
00:15:28,280 --> 00:15:31,280
Zero, zero, one.

324
00:15:31,280 --> 00:15:34,280
They are still orthogonal and normalized.

325
00:15:34,280 --> 00:15:36,280
This zero should go here.

326
00:15:36,280 --> 00:15:39,280
So up and down are at right angles.

327
00:15:39,280 --> 00:15:43,280
Up and down in the space of states.

328
00:15:43,280 --> 00:15:47,280
Not in...

329
00:15:47,280 --> 00:15:50,280
We're going to have to remember the difference

330
00:15:50,280 --> 00:15:52,280
between these vectors,

331
00:15:52,280 --> 00:15:55,280
these abstract vectors which represent states,

332
00:15:55,280 --> 00:15:56,280
and vectors in real space,

333
00:15:56,280 --> 00:15:58,280
because that's going to come up today.

334
00:15:58,280 --> 00:16:01,280
So we're going to have to remember the difference

335
00:16:01,280 --> 00:16:03,280
between these vectors.

336
00:16:03,280 --> 00:16:06,280
And we'll label them slightly differently.

337
00:16:06,280 --> 00:16:08,280
All right, now.

338
00:16:08,280 --> 00:16:12,280
What about the quantities that you measure?

339
00:16:12,280 --> 00:16:14,280
They are called observables.

340
00:16:14,280 --> 00:16:16,280
They're the things that you measure.

341
00:16:16,280 --> 00:16:18,280
And by assumption,

342
00:16:18,280 --> 00:16:20,280
there may be more than one thing

343
00:16:20,280 --> 00:16:25,280
that you can measure about a system.

344
00:16:25,280 --> 00:16:27,280
And you can always reduce them to real numbers.

345
00:16:27,280 --> 00:16:28,280
The results of a measurement

346
00:16:28,280 --> 00:16:33,280
are always a collection of real numbers.

347
00:16:33,280 --> 00:16:36,280
You may combine them together, for example,

348
00:16:36,280 --> 00:16:38,280
into a complex number,

349
00:16:38,280 --> 00:16:40,280
but the results of real measurements,

350
00:16:40,280 --> 00:16:43,280
you know, pointers on a dial or whatever,

351
00:16:43,280 --> 00:16:46,280
are real numbers.

352
00:16:46,280 --> 00:16:49,280
And so observables

353
00:16:49,280 --> 00:16:51,280
are things which, when you measure them,

354
00:16:51,280 --> 00:16:53,280
among other things,

355
00:16:53,280 --> 00:16:56,280
you get real numbers as a result.

356
00:16:56,280 --> 00:17:00,280
They are represented by matrices or operators.

357
00:17:00,280 --> 00:17:01,280
Strictly speaking,

358
00:17:01,280 --> 00:17:04,280
they're represented by linear operators,

359
00:17:04,280 --> 00:17:06,280
which you can take to

360
00:17:06,280 --> 00:17:08,280
just being matrices for our purpose.

361
00:17:08,280 --> 00:17:10,280
But a special class of matrices,

362
00:17:10,280 --> 00:17:12,280
the Hermitian matrices.

363
00:17:12,280 --> 00:17:16,280
Hermitian, H-E-R-M-I-T-I-A-N.

364
00:17:16,280 --> 00:17:18,280
Hermitian for Hermite,

365
00:17:18,280 --> 00:17:21,280
and Hermite was a mathematician.

366
00:17:21,280 --> 00:17:23,280
Hermitian matrices.

367
00:17:23,280 --> 00:17:24,280
And to define them,

368
00:17:24,280 --> 00:17:26,280
let's first define

369
00:17:26,280 --> 00:17:29,280
a couple of concepts about matrices.

370
00:17:29,280 --> 00:17:30,280
First of all,

371
00:17:30,280 --> 00:17:33,280
there's the concept of the transpose of a matrix.

372
00:17:33,280 --> 00:17:36,280
The transpose of a matrix...

373
00:17:43,280 --> 00:17:46,280
You have diagonal elements and off-diagonal elements.

374
00:17:46,280 --> 00:17:48,280
And there's no reason why it has to be 2x2.

375
00:17:48,280 --> 00:17:50,280
Let's take it to be 3x3.

376
00:17:50,280 --> 00:17:55,280
There's M11, M22, M33.

377
00:17:55,280 --> 00:17:58,280
And then there's the off-diagonal elements.

378
00:17:58,280 --> 00:18:00,280
Let's just put one of them over here.

379
00:18:00,280 --> 00:18:03,280
Here's M12.

380
00:18:03,280 --> 00:18:05,280
And here's M21, and so forth.

381
00:18:05,280 --> 00:18:08,280
And there's other ones, other...

382
00:18:08,280 --> 00:18:10,280
They're all there.

383
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:14,280
The transpose of a matrix is just...

384
00:18:14,280 --> 00:18:19,280
You act on the matrix to interchange rows and columns.

385
00:18:19,280 --> 00:18:23,280
All it means is you reflect it about the diagonal.

386
00:18:23,280 --> 00:18:24,280
You just imagine it's written on a piece of paper,

387
00:18:24,280 --> 00:18:27,280
and you turn over the piece of paper

388
00:18:27,280 --> 00:18:33,280
so that M12 replaces M21, and so forth.

389
00:18:33,280 --> 00:18:35,280
The way to write that,

390
00:18:35,280 --> 00:18:37,280
the transpose...

391
00:18:37,280 --> 00:18:39,280
The transpose is just written

392
00:18:39,280 --> 00:18:41,280
by putting a T up here.

393
00:18:41,280 --> 00:18:43,280
And it's just...

394
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:46,280
The diagonal elements are unchanged.

395
00:18:48,280 --> 00:18:51,280
But the off-diagonal elements,

396
00:18:51,280 --> 00:18:53,280
M12 becomes M21,

397
00:18:53,280 --> 00:18:58,280
and M12, they just interchange.

398
00:18:58,280 --> 00:19:01,280
And likewise over here and so forth.

399
00:19:01,280 --> 00:19:05,280
Okay, that's called the transpose.

400
00:19:05,280 --> 00:19:07,280
We can write that in the form...

401
00:19:07,280 --> 00:19:10,280
The transpose matrix,

402
00:19:10,280 --> 00:19:13,280
we can call it ij, the ijth element of it,

403
00:19:13,280 --> 00:19:15,780
is just the j i

404
00:19:15,780 --> 00:19:18,280
th element of the original matrix.

405
00:19:18,280 --> 00:19:22,280
Interchange of i and j, of rows and columns.

406
00:19:22,280 --> 00:19:24,280
It's called transpose.

407
00:19:27,280 --> 00:19:31,280
The next concept is the Hermitian conjugate.

408
00:19:31,280 --> 00:19:32,280
I'll write it out.

409
00:19:32,280 --> 00:19:34,280
Hermitian conjugate.

410
00:19:34,280 --> 00:19:39,280
And it's a kind of complex conjugation.

411
00:19:39,280 --> 00:19:42,280
A complex conjugation for matrices.

412
00:19:42,280 --> 00:19:44,280
Hermitian conjugate.

413
00:19:46,280 --> 00:19:48,280
And it involves two operations.

414
00:19:48,280 --> 00:19:51,280
The first is to transpose,

415
00:19:51,280 --> 00:19:54,280
and then to complex conjugate.

416
00:19:54,280 --> 00:19:58,280
And it's represented by a dagger.

417
00:20:06,280 --> 00:20:09,280
It's represented by a dagger.

418
00:20:09,280 --> 00:20:13,280
And it's represented by first of all transposing,

419
00:20:13,280 --> 00:20:17,280
but then complex conjugating everything.

420
00:20:17,280 --> 00:20:19,280
All the elements.

421
00:20:19,280 --> 00:20:21,280
The diagonal elements,

422
00:20:21,280 --> 00:20:23,280
as well as the off-diagonal elements.

423
00:20:23,280 --> 00:20:26,280
And we write it by saying that

424
00:20:26,280 --> 00:20:29,280
the Hermitian conjugate,

425
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:33,280
the dagger of a matrix,

426
00:20:33,280 --> 00:20:36,280
is you interchange rows and columns,

427
00:20:36,280 --> 00:20:39,280
and then you complex conjugate.

428
00:20:42,280 --> 00:20:45,280
All right, so let's do an example.

429
00:20:45,280 --> 00:20:47,280
Here's an example.

430
00:20:47,280 --> 00:20:50,280
Four plus two i,

431
00:20:50,280 --> 00:20:53,280
seven minus i,

432
00:20:53,280 --> 00:20:56,280
six plus four i,

433
00:20:56,280 --> 00:20:59,280
and nine minus two i.

434
00:20:59,280 --> 00:21:02,280
All right, what's the dagger?

435
00:21:02,280 --> 00:21:05,280
The Hermitian conjugate of that matrix?

436
00:21:05,280 --> 00:21:08,280
Well, the diagonal elements,

437
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:10,280
they don't move when you transpose.

438
00:21:10,280 --> 00:21:13,280
Transposing a diagonal element stays in the same place,

439
00:21:13,280 --> 00:21:15,280
but we have to complex conjugate it.

440
00:21:15,280 --> 00:21:18,280
So we get four minus two i.

441
00:21:18,280 --> 00:21:20,280
Now, the element up here,

442
00:21:20,280 --> 00:21:22,280
first we have to transpose.

443
00:21:22,280 --> 00:21:24,280
What was this, four?

444
00:21:24,280 --> 00:21:26,280
Four minus two i? Yeah, okay.

445
00:21:26,280 --> 00:21:28,280
We have to transpose, which means we put,

446
00:21:28,280 --> 00:21:31,280
we interchange rows and columns,

447
00:21:31,280 --> 00:21:34,280
and then complex conjugate.

448
00:21:34,280 --> 00:21:37,280
So then we get four plus two i up here.

449
00:21:37,280 --> 00:21:41,280
We put this one complex conjugated.

450
00:21:41,280 --> 00:21:43,280
This one complex conjugated goes down here,

451
00:21:43,280 --> 00:21:45,280
six minus four i.

452
00:21:45,280 --> 00:21:50,280
And the diagonal matrix element stays where it is,

453
00:21:50,280 --> 00:21:52,280
but it gets complex conjugated,

454
00:21:52,280 --> 00:21:54,280
seven plus i.

455
00:21:54,280 --> 00:21:58,280
All right, so that's the idea of

456
00:21:58,280 --> 00:22:00,280
Hermitian conjugation.

457
00:22:00,280 --> 00:22:02,280
Flip the rows and columns,

458
00:22:02,280 --> 00:22:09,280
and then complex conjugate.

459
00:22:09,280 --> 00:22:11,280
A Hermitian matrix,

460
00:22:11,280 --> 00:22:14,280
well, first let's talk about symmetric matrices.

461
00:22:14,280 --> 00:22:16,280
Symmetric matrices,

462
00:22:16,280 --> 00:22:19,280
let's just go back to the idea of transpose,

463
00:22:19,280 --> 00:22:28,280
without the complex conjugation.

464
00:22:28,280 --> 00:22:32,280
Just the transpose.

465
00:22:32,280 --> 00:22:35,280
A symmetric matrix is one that

466
00:22:35,280 --> 00:22:38,280
is equal to its own transpose.

467
00:22:38,280 --> 00:22:40,280
In other words, when you transpose it,

468
00:22:40,280 --> 00:22:42,280
you get back the same thing.

469
00:22:42,280 --> 00:22:44,280
In order for that to be the case,

470
00:22:44,280 --> 00:22:50,280
all that you need is that the elements,

471
00:22:50,280 --> 00:22:54,280
the reflected elements are the same as each other.

472
00:22:54,280 --> 00:22:57,780
So it would say that m to one

473
00:22:57,780 --> 00:23:01,280
has to be equal to m one two.

474
00:23:01,280 --> 00:23:04,280
So put the same m to one here.

475
00:23:04,280 --> 00:23:06,280
That's the idea of a symmetric matrix,

476
00:23:06,280 --> 00:23:09,280
and it just is exactly what it says.

477
00:23:09,280 --> 00:23:12,280
It's sort of symmetric with respect to flipping it

478
00:23:12,280 --> 00:23:15,280
or to reflecting it about the main diagonal.

479
00:23:15,280 --> 00:23:18,280
A symmetric matrix satisfies

480
00:23:18,280 --> 00:23:22,280
m i j equals m j i.

481
00:23:22,280 --> 00:23:24,280
That's a symmetric matrix.

482
00:23:24,280 --> 00:23:26,280
Very simple concept.

483
00:23:26,280 --> 00:23:30,280
A Hermitian matrix is a little more complicated.

484
00:23:30,280 --> 00:23:32,280
And what it says,

485
00:23:32,280 --> 00:23:35,280
a Hermitian matrix is a matrix which

486
00:23:35,280 --> 00:23:38,280
is equal to its own Hermitian conjugate.

487
00:23:38,280 --> 00:23:40,280
So if you have a matrix,

488
00:23:40,280 --> 00:23:43,280
and you Hermitian conjugate it,

489
00:23:43,280 --> 00:23:45,280
if it is equal to the original matrix,

490
00:23:45,280 --> 00:23:47,280
it's called Hermitian.

491
00:23:47,280 --> 00:23:49,280
It's just called Hermitian.

492
00:23:49,280 --> 00:23:52,280
That's the definition of a Hermitian matrix.

493
00:23:52,280 --> 00:23:55,280
Let's write a Hermitian matrix down.

494
00:23:55,280 --> 00:24:00,280
Actually, you could write the formula for it,

495
00:24:00,280 --> 00:24:03,280
and then do the example.

496
00:24:03,280 --> 00:24:06,280
Write the formula for it, yes.

497
00:24:06,280 --> 00:24:08,280
Yes, yes.

498
00:24:08,280 --> 00:24:11,280
There's the formula for it right here.

499
00:24:11,280 --> 00:24:16,280
m i j is m i j complex conjugate.

500
00:24:16,280 --> 00:24:18,280
All right.

501
00:24:18,280 --> 00:24:21,280
Now, say it again.

502
00:24:21,280 --> 00:24:25,280
I think it's written correctly.

503
00:24:25,280 --> 00:24:28,280
m i j is m i m j i conjugate.

504
00:24:28,280 --> 00:24:32,280
It's correct.

505
00:24:32,280 --> 00:24:34,280
What it says, first of all,

506
00:24:34,280 --> 00:24:37,280
is that the diagonal elements are real.

507
00:24:37,280 --> 00:24:39,280
For example, this says,

508
00:24:39,280 --> 00:24:41,280
if you interchange i and j on a diagonal element,

509
00:24:41,280 --> 00:24:44,280
you just get the same diagonal element.

510
00:24:44,280 --> 00:24:46,780
So it says that m i 1

511
00:24:46,780 --> 00:24:49,280
is equal to m i 1 star.

512
00:24:49,280 --> 00:24:52,280
That means that m i 1 is real.

513
00:24:52,280 --> 00:24:58,280
So, real numbers on the diagonal.

514
00:24:58,280 --> 00:25:00,280
Not all is the same real number.

515
00:25:00,280 --> 00:25:03,280
I mean, I just wrote real, real, real, real,

516
00:25:03,280 --> 00:25:06,280
meaning any real number in any one of these places.

517
00:25:06,280 --> 00:25:09,280
And then on the off-diagonal elements over here,

518
00:25:09,280 --> 00:25:13,280
let's suppose that this off-diagonal element over here is z,

519
00:25:13,280 --> 00:25:16,280
the complex number z,

520
00:25:16,280 --> 00:25:19,280
then the reflected off-diagonal element

521
00:25:19,280 --> 00:25:21,280
has to be the complex conjugate.

522
00:25:21,280 --> 00:25:23,280
Then it's called Hermitian.

523
00:25:23,280 --> 00:25:25,280
So,

524
00:25:25,280 --> 00:25:29,780
2, 7, 1 plus i

525
00:25:29,780 --> 00:25:34,280
and 1 minus i is Hermitian.

526
00:25:34,280 --> 00:25:35,280
Real elements on the diagonal,

527
00:25:35,280 --> 00:25:42,280
and complex conjugates when you reflect.

528
00:25:42,280 --> 00:25:45,280
This is a kind of reality property.

529
00:25:45,280 --> 00:25:48,280
A thing being its own complex conjugate for a number

530
00:25:48,280 --> 00:25:50,280
says that it's real.

531
00:25:50,280 --> 00:25:53,280
For a matrix, the concept of reality

532
00:25:53,280 --> 00:25:56,280
is not that the matrix elements are all real,

533
00:25:56,280 --> 00:25:58,780
not that each matrix element

534
00:25:58,780 --> 00:26:01,280
separately is its own complex conjugate,

535
00:26:01,280 --> 00:26:04,280
but each matrix element is the complex conjugate

536
00:26:04,280 --> 00:26:07,280
of the reflected matrix element.

537
00:26:07,280 --> 00:26:08,280
We'll find out.

538
00:26:08,280 --> 00:26:09,780
We're going to see very shortly

539
00:26:09,780 --> 00:26:11,280
why this is a good definition.

540
00:26:16,280 --> 00:26:18,280
Okay, I'm going to write down some theorems.

541
00:26:18,280 --> 00:26:20,280
These are your homework to prove.

542
00:26:20,280 --> 00:26:22,280
They're very, very simple.

543
00:26:22,280 --> 00:26:26,280
But just,

544
00:26:26,280 --> 00:26:29,280
they don't have names because they're too simple.

545
00:26:31,280 --> 00:26:33,280
Very elementary theorems.

546
00:26:34,280 --> 00:26:36,280
First of all, if you take two vectors,

547
00:26:36,280 --> 00:26:37,280
A and B,

548
00:26:37,280 --> 00:26:43,280
and you take the inner product of A with B,

549
00:26:43,280 --> 00:26:47,280
now remember, when you form the row vector B,

